</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="58.[151,1437,151,901]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">
<emphasis box="[199,367,479,504]" italics="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Cephalothorax</emphasis>
. Frontal apotome conical (
<figureCitation box="[692,796,479,504]" captionStart="FIGURES 106–109" captionStartId="57.[151,264,1799,1821]" captionTargetBox="[274,1320,192,1770]" captionTargetId="figure-124@57.[226,1360,147,1810]" captionTargetPageId="57" captionText="FIGURES 106–109. Beardius phoenix sp. n., pupa. 106—frontal apotome; 107—thoracic horn; 108—paratergite VIII; 109— abdominal segments I–IX and anal lobe, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5270958" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5270958/files/figure.png" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Fig. 106</figureCitation>
), frontal setae 33–55 µm long. Thoracic horn with 5 branches (
<figureCitation box="[266,365,516,541]" captionStart="FIGURES 106–109" captionStartId="57.[151,264,1799,1821]" captionTargetBox="[274,1320,192,1770]" captionTargetId="figure-124@57.[226,1360,147,1810]" captionTargetPageId="57" captionText="FIGURES 106–109. Beardius phoenix sp. n., pupa. 106—frontal apotome; 107—thoracic horn; 108—paratergite VIII; 109— abdominal segments I–IX and anal lobe, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5270958" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5270958/files/figure.png" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Fig. 107</figureCitation>
); anterior branch with spinules along distal 1/2. Distance between Dc1 and Dc2 8 µm; between Dc2 and Dc3 138 µm; between Dc3 and Dc4 8 µm. Prealars absent.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="58.[151,1437,151,901]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">
<emphasis box="[199,305,588,613]" italics="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Abdomen</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[321,420,588,613]" captionStart="FIGURES 106–109" captionStartId="57.[151,264,1799,1821]" captionTargetBox="[274,1320,192,1770]" captionTargetId="figure-124@57.[226,1360,147,1810]" captionTargetPageId="57" captionText="FIGURES 106–109. Beardius phoenix sp. n., pupa. 106—frontal apotome; 107—thoracic horn; 108—paratergite VIII; 109— abdominal segments I–IX and anal lobe, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5270958" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5270958/files/figure.png" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Fig. 109</figureCitation>
). Tergites I, VII and VIII without shagreen. Tergites II–V with anterior transverse band of shagreen a little stronger than contiguous posterior shagreen. Tergite VI with anterior transverse band of shagreen only. Row of hooklets on tergite II about 1/3 of tergite width. Conjunctive IV/V with spinules in a single patch. Paratergite V with few spinules, restricted to posterior margin. Pedes spurii A and pedes spurii B present. Segment I without L setae; segments II–IV with 3 setae L; segment V with 3 taeniate L setae; segments VI–VIII with 4 taeniate L setae. Segment VIII without lateral spines, spur simple (
<figureCitation box="[940,1043,767,792]" captionStart="FIGURES 106–109" captionStartId="57.[151,264,1799,1821]" captionTargetBox="[274,1320,192,1770]" captionTargetId="figure-124@57.[226,1360,147,1810]" captionTargetPageId="57" captionText="FIGURES 106–109. Beardius phoenix sp. n., pupa. 106—frontal apotome; 107—thoracic horn; 108—paratergite VIII; 109— abdominal segments I–IX and anal lobe, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5270958" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5270958/files/figure.png" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Fig. 108</figureCitation>
). Anal lobe 106 µm long, with 8 taeniate setae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="58.[151,1437,151,901]" box="[199,539,839,864]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,414,839,864]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Female and larva.</emphasis>
Unknown.
</paragraph>
